    <stitle>DT/DTI-466 A and B Series DT/DTI/DTA-466 C Diesel Engine Diagnostics (1993) - ENGINE DIAGNOSTIC TEST
        PROCEDURES - DT/DTI - 466 A AND B SERIES DIESEL ENGINES - SHUT-OFF CABLE DT/DTI-466 A and B Series (With UTDS
        Model 100 Fuel Injection Pump) - Inspection and Repair
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="0">
        <title>Inspection and Repair</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Visually inspect electric shut-off components as indicated in the Visual Inspection Chart.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Replace any wom or damaged component.</para>
        </step1>
        <table id="t4500505">
            <tgroup cols="3">
                <colspec colname="1" colwidth="144p"/>
                <colspec colname="2" colwidth="144p"/>
                <colspec colname="3" colwidth="144p"/>
                <spanspec namest="1" nameend="3" spanname="S1T3"/>
                <tbody>
                    <row>
                        <entry colspan="3" spanname="S1T3">
                            <para>ESO VISUAL INSPECTION CHART</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>Part</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>Inspect for the following condition(s)</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="3">
                            <para>Corrective Action When Required</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>
                                <emph type="bold">Control Unit Cover</emph>
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>
                                <emph type="bold">Cracked or damaged.</emph>
                            </para>
                            <para>
                                <emph type="bold">Damaged threads</emph>
                            </para>
                            <para>
                                <emph type="bold">Scratched sealing surface.</emph>
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="3">
                            <para>
                                <emph type="bold">Replace cover</emph>
                            </para>
                            <para></para>
                            <para></para>
                            <para></para>
                            <para>
                                <emph type="bold">Refinish sealing surface.</emph>
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>Plunger</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>Excessive wear,nicks, bends, and a free fit into the control unit cover.</para>
                            <para>Loose spring retaining ring.</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="3">
                            <para>Replace solenoid assembly.</para>
                            <para></para>
                            <para></para>
                            <para>Replace spring retaining ring.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>Plunger return spring</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>Broken or damaged (See note)</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="3">
                            <para>Replace spring</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>Solenoid</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>Damaged or cracked. Damaged threads or I.D. Loose or broken insulator at terminal end.
                                (See note)
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="3">
                            <para>Replace solenoid</para>
                            <para>assembly.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>Screws, washers and lock washers</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>Damaged</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="3">
                            <para>Replace.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry colname="1">
                            <para>"O" rings, gaskets and lock wire</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="2">
                            <para>Not reusable</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry colname="3">
                            <para>Replace.</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </tbody>
            </tgroup>
        </table>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>The solenoid should be tested as follows:</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Measure plunger return spring for overall length. A new spring of approximately 1.9 inches
                is now used in all solenoids. If spring measures 3 inches, replace spring with new 1.9 inch spring. If
                spring is otherwise damaged or broken, replace spring.
            </emph>
        </para>
        <para>Perform Functional and Electrical Tests as Follows:</para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Assemble ring
                <emph type="bold">(6, Figure
                    <hotlnk document="e450_65.xml" xrefid="ef4500511">5.11</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ), washer (5) and spring (3) onto plunger (4); insert plunger into solenoid ( 1). Install solenoid with
                gasket (2) on control unit cover (10) and tighten to specified torque.
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use a DC power source and apply 10 volts to terminal of a 12 volt solenoid. An ammeter
                    in series with solenoid should read from 2.1 to 2.3 AMPS (4.3 to 4.8 0HMS).
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Apply 20 volts to terminal of a 24 volt solenoid. An ammeter in series with solenoid
                    should read from 1.0 to 1.1 AMPS (17.4 to 19.2 OHMS).
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Both 12 and 24 volt solenoids should retract and extend rapidly as electrical circuit
                    with respective voltage is turned on and off.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Remove solenoid assembly from control unit cover in preparation for assembly to pump.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
